member.example:
The following code creates a Dictionary where the keys are a collection of strings.

    Dictionary<IEnumerable<String>, Int32> =
        new Dictionary<IEnumerable<String>, Int32>(Algorithms.GetCollectionEqualityComparer<String>());

The following code creates a Dictionary where the keys are a collection of strings, compared in a case-insensitive way

    Dictionary<IEnumerable<String>, Int32> =
        new Dictionary<IEnumerable<String>, Int32>(Algorithms.GetCollectionEqualityComparer<String>(StringComparer.CurrentCultureIgnoreCase));

The following code creates a Dictionary where the keys are a set of strings, without regard to order

    Dictionary<IEnumerable<String>, Int32> =
        new Dictionary<IEnumerable<String>, Int32>(Algorithms.GetSetEqualityComparer<String>(StringComparer.CurrentCultureIgnoreCase));

The following code creates a Dictionary where the keys are a set of strings, without regard to order

    Dictionary<IEnumerable<String>, Int32> =
        new Dictionary<IEnumerable<String>, Int32>(Algorithms.GetSetEqualityComparer<String>());

member.remarks:
Since an arbitrary BinaryPredicate is passed to this function, what is being tested
            for need not be equality. For example, the following code determines if each integer in
            list1 is less than or equal to the corresponding integer in list2.

            List<Int32> list1, list2;
            if (EqualCollections(list1, list2, delegate(Int32 x, Int32 y) { return x <= y; }) {
                // the check is true...
            }

